## Development guardrails

Behavioral guardrails that reduce common AI-coding mistakes — adapted from
[multica-ai/andrej-karpathy-skills](https://github.com/multica-ai/andrej-karpathy-skills)
(MIT, per its README), after Andrej Karpathy's notes on LLM coding pitfalls. They
bias toward caution over speed; use judgment on trivial changes.

- **Think before coding.** State assumptions; when intent is ambiguous, ask instead of guessing. Surface tradeoffs and push back when a simpler path exists.
- **Simplicity first.** Write the minimum code that solves the task — no speculative abstractions, options, or handling for impossible cases. If 200 lines could be 50, rewrite it.
- **Surgical changes.** Touch only what the task requires; don't refactor or reformat adjacent code, match the existing style, and flag unrelated dead code rather than deleting it.
- **Goal-driven execution.** Turn each task into a verifiable goal — write the failing test, then make it pass — and loop until the criteria are met.

